<DESCRIPT>  MATH; EDUCATION  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  HERE are some sources of information for parents helping children to learn and
enjoy mathematics.;    (check) The Family Math Network holds classes in the
Bay Area for kids and their parents on ways to make math fun. There is usually
no fee. Classes are held in English or Spanish; for a schedule, call (415)
528-0560. A book, "Family Math," is also available in English and Spanish. To
order, send a check for $15, plus sales tax and $4 for shipping, to: Lawrence
Hall of Science, University of California, Berkeley, Calif. 94720. For
information about the book, call (415) 642-1823.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Science &amp; Medicine  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  MORE STRATEGIES FOR TEACHING MATH  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  See also related story on page 2E of this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     (check) A "home helper" kit developed by the PTA contains 70 simple math
activities for parents and kids, from exploring the geometry of the Golden
Arches to figuring batting averages. The kit includes a calculator and a
seven-minute videotape. A limited number of Spanish kits is available for
free; the English kit is $10. Order from: Mathematical Sciences Education
Board, Attention: Ann Kahn, 818 Connecticut Ave. N.W., Suite 500, Washington,
D.C. 20006. For information, call (202) 334-3294.;    (check) "The Changing
Mathematics Curriculum: A Booklet for Parents," is a 12-page booklet on what
to expect in your child's math classroom. Booklets are $5 for 10 or $30 for
100. Order from: Bureau of Publications Sales Unit, California Department of
Education, P.O. Box 271, Sacramento, Calif. 95802-0271. For information, call
(916) 445-1260.  </TEXT>
<BYLINE>  -- Glennda Chui  </BYLINE>
